ctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding stone epidemiology and natural history is important for patient education and management. \u003Cstrong\u003EUric acid stones\u003C/strong\u003E account for approximately 5-10% of all urinary stones, with calcium-based stones being most common (80%). \u003Cstrong\u003EMost 3mm stones\u003C/strong\u003E will be passed spontaneously (~75%). This likelihood of spontaneous passage decreases as stone size increases. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E50% of patients\u003C/strong\u003E who develop one stone will experience a recurrence within 5-10 years, highlighting the importance of prevention strategies. \u003Cstrong\u003EThe most common locations\u003C/strong\u003E for stone obstruction are the ureteropelvic junction, the crossing of iliac vessels, and the ureterovesical junction. \u003Cstrong\u003EMen\u003C/strong\u003E are affected 2-3 times more commonly than women.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The most common sites of urinary stone obstruction are the ureteropelvic junction, ureterovesical junction, and crossing of iliac vessels","50% of people who develop one kidney stone will have a recurrence within 5-10 years"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Fontenelle LF, Sarti TD. Kidney Stones: Treatment and Prevention. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Apr 15;99(8):490-496. PMID: 30990297.","Peerapen P, Thongboonkerd V. Kidney Stone Prevention. Adv Nutr. 2023 May;14(3):555-569. doi: 10.1016/j.advnut.2023.03.002. Epub 2023 Mar 9. PMID: 36906146; PMCID: PMC10201681."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51301"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15018"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]}